Yiwen Xu, Kehan Zhang, Shuang Liang, Christopher Deng Jr¶

1 Data Preparation¶

For this lab, we pick this dataset that is a collection of images of human faces that was created two years ago. Some of them are wearing a mask, some of them are not. Images with face mask are scrapped rom google search and images without a face mask are gathered from the CelebFace dataset(https://www.kaggle.com/jessicali9530).

This dataset is gathered to create a mask detection algorithm. The algorithm can detect if the person is wearing a mask or not. It can be widely used in public places and in private areas. Government can be interested in these results as it can be used to track down people who are not wearing mask in case there’s a disease outbreak. People who are not wearing a mask are more prone to get the disease and to spread the disease. The government can use this data to better warn people and stop the disease from spreading. Using the data, the government can have a big advantage in their effort in predicting how the disease will spread and can save a lot of time and money. Private labs and factories can also be interested in these results as well. They can used this to make sure workers are wearing their mask so they can prevent workers from breathing in toxic materials and stop accidents from happening. Hospital is another party that can be interested in the result. Hospitals can use it to make sure that the doctors and nurses are wearing the mask as required. So, both the patients and employees can be safe.

a = os.walk(r'Face_Mask_Dataset/Train')
for root,dirs,files in os.walk(r'Face_Mask_Dataset/Train'):
    i = 0
    for name in files:
        if ".DS_Store" not in name:# It's a Problem that macos's unzip file have,just ignore it.
            img_path = os.path.join(root, name)            
            I = cv2.imread(img_path,cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE) # to grayscale
            I2 = cv2.imread(img_path, cv2.IMREAD_COLOR)[:, :, ::-1]
            
            image_arr = cv2.resize(I,dim) # resize to dim we set
            image_arr2 = cv2.resize(I2,dim) # resize to dim we set
            
            image_arr = image_arr.reshape(1,image_arr.size) # make it array
            dataset_rgb.append(image_arr2) # save for exceptional work
            
            label = (str(os.path.basename(os.path.dirname(img_path))))
            if label == 'WithMask':
                label = int(1)
            else:
                label = int(0)
            
            dataset_target = np.row_stack((dataset_target,label))
            dataset_data = np.row_stack((dataset_data,image_arr))
            i = i+1
            if(i==max_quantity_per_class):
                i = 0
                break
                
dataset_rgb = np.array(dataset_rgb)

1.2 The Metric that are going to use to evaluate our algorithm’s performance.¶

Here we choose to use the Precision as the metric to evaluate the peroformance. Here is the reason:

In this project we want to classify whether people in the picture is wearing or not the mask. For any potential third party user/organization, it is obviously a huge problem if the model says they wear the mask but actually they are not. Even tiny mistake could couse huge problem, especially in some lab, hospital and chemical plant. It would lead to some serious safety problem. That is, we want the metric focus on the lowest false postives(FP) rather then other. The metric percision, which is caculate by $(TP) /(TP+FP)$.

1.3 Dividing the Data¶

For diving our data, we choose to do the 80/20 split. We choose to do this because we have enough data entries over 10K. We also believe that we don't need to do cross validation also because we have enough data entries so over fitting shouldn't occur.

# initialize image data generator for later use

datagen = ImageDataGenerator(
    featurewise_center=False,
    samplewise_center=False,
    featurewise_std_normalization=False,
    samplewise_std_normalization=False,
    zca_whitening=False,
    rotation_range=45, # used, Int. Degree range for random rotations.
    width_shift_range=0.1, # used, Float (fraction of total width). Range for random horizontal shifts.
    height_shift_range=0.1, # used,  Float (fraction of total height). Range for random vertical shifts.
    shear_range=0., # Float. Shear Intensity (Shear angle in counter-clockwise direction as radians)
    zoom_range=0.2,
    channel_shift_range=0.,
    fill_mode='nearest',
    cval=0.,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    vertical_flip=False,
    rescale=None)

datagen.fit(X_train)

# Add augmented data to training data set
X_new, y_new = datagen.flow(X_train, y_train, batch_size=int(len(X_train)/5)).next()

Through comparing the images above, we decided to expand our training dataset with rotation, zoom and shift techniques. This is because we have reason to consider that there may be many different cameras capturing the instantaneous situation. We also used only the horizontal flip technique to further distinguish the expanded data from the original data, since it is rarely possible to apply this model to upside-down images.

# helper function that plots training recall history, validation recall history, 
# training BCE loss history, and validation BCE loss history

from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

%matplotlib inline

def plot_history(model_history):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
    plt.subplot(2,2,1)
    plt.plot(list(model_history.history.values())[1])

    plt.ylabel('Precision')
    plt.title('Training')
    plt.subplot(2,2,2)
    plt.plot(list(model_history.history.values())[3])
    plt.title('Validation')

    plt.subplot(2,2,3)
    plt.plot(model_history.history['loss'])
    plt.ylabel('Training Loss')
    plt.xlabel('epochs')

    plt.subplot(2,2,4)
    plt.plot(model_history.history['val_loss'])
    plt.xlabel('epochs')
    
    plt.show()

def show_confusion_matrix(cnn, X_test, y_test, labels='auto', title_text='CNN:'):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    yhat = np.round(cnn.predict(X_test))
    acc = mt.precision_score(y_test,yhat)
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    cm = mt.confusion_matrix(y_test,yhat)
    cm = cm/np.sum(cm,axis=1)[:,np.newaxis]
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='.2f', xticklabels=labels,yticklabels=labels)
    plt.title(title_text+'{:.4f}'.format(acc))

2.2.1 AlexNet Architecture(Filters: 16, 32)¶

In [22]:
%%time 

cnn_alexnet_16 = Sequential()

# let's start with an AlexNet style convolutional phase
cnn_alexnet_16.add(Conv2D(filters=16,
                input_shape = (img_wh,img_wh,1),
                kernel_size=(3,3), 
                padding='same', 
                activation='relu', data_format="channels_last")) # more compact syntax

# no max pool before next conv layer!!
cnn_alexnet_16.add(Conv2D(filters=32,
                kernel_size=(3,3), 
                padding='same', 
                activation='relu')) # more compact syntax
cnn_alexnet_16.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_last"))
    
# add one layer on flattened output
cnn_alexnet_16.add(Dropout(0.25)) # add some dropout for regularization after conv layers
cnn_alexnet_16.add(Flatten())
cnn_alexnet_16.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
cnn_alexnet_16.add(Dropout(0.5)) # add some dropout for regularization, again!
cnn_alexnet_16.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

cnn_alexnet_16.summary()

# Let's train the model 
cnn_alexnet_16.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', # 'categorical_crossentropy' 'mean_squared_error'
              optimizer='adam', # 'adadelta' 'rmsprop'
              metrics=keras.metrics.Precision())

# the flow method yields batches of images indefinitely, with the given transformations
cnn_alexnet_16_history = cnn_alexnet_16.fit(X_train, y_train,
                   epochs=20, verbose=1, validation_data=(X_test,y_test)
                  )

%%time

from tensorflow.keras.layers import Add, Input
from tensorflow.keras.layers import average, concatenate
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model

l2_lambda = 0.000001

input_holder = Input(shape=(img_wh, img_wh, 1))

# start with a conv layer
x = Conv2D(filters=16,
               input_shape = (img_wh,img_wh,1),
               kernel_size=(3,3),
               kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
               kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
               padding='same', 
               activation='relu', 
               data_format="channels_last")(input_holder)

x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_last")(x)

x = Conv2D(filters=16,
               kernel_size=(3,3),
               kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
               kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
               padding='same', 
               activation='relu', 
               data_format="channels_last")(x)

x_split = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_last")(x)

x = Conv2D(filters=32,
               kernel_size=(1,1),
               kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
               kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
               padding='same', 
               activation='relu', 
               data_format="channels_last")(x_split)

x = Conv2D(filters=32,
               kernel_size=(3,3),
               kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
               kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
               padding='same', 
               activation='relu', 
               data_format="channels_last")(x)

x = Conv2D(filters=16,
               kernel_size=(1,1),
               kernel_initializer='he_uniform', 
               kernel_regularizer=l2(l2_lambda),
               padding='same', 
               activation='relu', 
               data_format="channels_last")(x)

# now add back in the split layer, x_split (residual added in)
x = Add()([x, x_split])
x = Activation("relu")(x)

x = MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), data_format="channels_last")(x)

x = Flatten()(x)
x = Dropout(0.25)(x)
x = Dense(128)(x)
x = Activation("relu")(x)
x = Dropout(0.5)(x)
x = Dense(1)(x)
x = Activation('sigmoid')(x)

cnn_resnet_16 = Model(inputs=input_holder,outputs=x)

cnn_resnet_16.summary()

# Let's train the model 
cnn_resnet_16.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', # 'categorical_crossentropy' 'mean_squared_error'
              optimizer='adam', # 'adadelta' 'rmsprop'
              metrics=keras.metrics.Precision())

# the flow method yields batches of images indefinitely, with the given transformations
cnn_resnet_16_history = cnn_resnet_16.fit(X_train, y_train,
                   epochs=20, verbose=1, validation_data=(X_test,y_test)
                  )

def create_contingency_McNemar(y_test, model1_pred, model2_pred):
    
    correct1_correct2 = 0  # model 1 predict correctly, model 2 also predict correctly
    correct1_wrong2 = 0 # model 1 predict correctly, model 2 predict wrong
    wrong1_correct2 = 0
    wrong1_wrong2 = 0
    table = np.zeros([2, 2],dtype = int)
    
    for i in range(len(y_test)):
        if model1_pred[i] == y_test[i] and model2_pred[i] == y_test[i]:
            correct1_correct2 +=1
        elif model1_pred[i] == y_test[i] and model2_pred[i] != y_test[i]:
            correct1_wrong2 +=1
        elif model1_pred[i] != y_test[i] and model2_pred[i] == y_test[i]:
            wrong1_correct2 +=1
        else:
            wrong1_wrong2 +=1
    table[0][0] = int(correct1_correct2)
    table[0][1] = int(correct1_wrong2)
    table[1][0] = int(wrong1_correct2)
    table[1][1] = int(wrong1_wrong2)
    
    return table

from statsmodels.stats.contingency_tables import mcnemar

temp_table = create_contingency_McNemar(y_test, y_pred_1, y_pred_2)
result = mcnemar(temp_table, exact=True)

print('AlexNet_16 & AlexNet_32')
print('contingency_tables:')
print(temp_table)
print('caculate the McNemar')
print(result)
if result.pvalue < 0.05:
    print('Reject the Null hypothesis: Different proportions of errors.')
else:
    print('Take the Null hypothesis: Same proportions of errors.')

def compare_mlp_cnn(cnn, mlp, X_test, y_test, labels='auto'):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    if cnn is not None:
        yhat_cnn = np.round(cnn.predict(X_test))
        acc_cnn = mt.precision_score(y_test,yhat_cnn)
        plt.subplot(1,2,1)
        cm = mt.confusion_matrix(y_test,yhat_cnn)
        cm = cm/np.sum(cm,axis=1)[:,np.newaxis]
        sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='.2f',xticklabels=labels,yticklabels=labels)
        plt.title('CNN: '+str(acc_cnn))
    
    if mlp is not None:
        yhat_mlp = np.round(mlp.predict(X_test))
        acc_mlp = mt.precision_score(y_test,yhat_mlp)
        plt.subplot(1,2,2)
        cm = mt.confusion_matrix(y_test,yhat_mlp)
        cm = cm/np.sum(cm,axis=1)[:,np.newaxis]
        sns.heatmap(cm,annot=True, fmt='.2f',xticklabels=labels,yticklabels=labels)
        plt.title('MLP: '+str(acc_mlp))

3 Exceptional Work - Transfer Learning¶

We will use transfer learning with ResNet50. ResNet50 is a convolutional neural network which has 48 Convolution layer along with 1 MaxPool and 1 Average Pool layer. It has 3.8 x 10^9 Floating points operations. The pretrained network can classify images into 1000 object categories. As a result, the network has learned rich feature representations for a wide range of images.

Transfer learning with pretrained weight and networks allows us to take the learned weights from the extensive training already done and use those weights on a new classification task.
